<doc id="393055" wikidata="Q21285678" url="?curid=393055" title="Index set">
<text>In mathematics, an index set is a set whose members label (or index) members of another set. For instance, if the elements of a set may be &quot;indexed&quot; or &quot;labeled&quot; by means of the elements of a set , then is an index set. The indexing consists of a surjective function from onto , and the indexed collection is typically called an &quot;indexed family&quot;, often written as .

==Examples==
*An enumeration of a set gives an index set formula_1, where is the particular enumeration of .
*Any countably infinite set can be (injectively) indexed by the set of natural numbers formula_2.
*For formula_3, the indicator function on is the function formula_4 given by formula_5

The set of all such indicator functions, formula_6, is an uncountable set indexed by formula_7.

==Other uses==
In computational complexity theory and cryptography, an index set is a set for which there exists an algorithm that can sample the set efficiently; e.g., on input , can efficiently select a poly(n)-bit long element from the set.

==See also==
* Friendly-index set

